---
description: Core architecture constraints for the Go rewrite of Media Library Manager
alwaysApply: true
---

# Goal

Build Media Library Manager as a single Go application that fully replaces the existing Next.js/NestJS implementation.

# Migration intent

This repository currently contains an older reference implementation in:
- apps/web
- apps/api

These directories are reference only during migration.

The final goal is:
- one Go application
- root-level Go app structure
- removal of the old split-app structure when the Go implementation is ready

Do not design this as a permanent parallel multi-app repository.

# Stack

- Go
- net/http
- chi
- html/template
- embed
- MongoDB with the official Go driver

# Architecture rules

- Prefer full-page server rendering by default
- Use htmx only where partial HTML updates clearly improve UX
- Use vanilla JS only where browser-only behavior is required, especially barcode scanning
- Do not build a React-style SPA inside templates
- Do not split the final app into separate frontend/backend services
- Keep handlers thin
- Keep services business-focused
- Keep repositories persistence-only
- Keep provider integrations server-side only
- Keep the app HTML-first and form-first where practical

# Data model rules

Keep these collections:
- users
- sessions
- media_records
- library_entries
- optional provider_cache
- optional scan_logs

Do not:
- collapse canonical media metadata and user-owned entry state into one document shape
- move user-owned fields into media_records
- store raw provider payloads as the internal app schema

# Product rules

- Private login-first app
- Two buckets only: `catalog` and `wishlist`
- Media types: `movie`, `tv`, `album`, `book`, `game`
- Ratings are read-only external metadata only
- Barcode lookup is best-effort candidate matching
- Barcode lookup must never auto-save
- Explicit user action is required for add/import/save
- English and Japanese support
- Locale-prefixed page routes

# Auth rules

- username/password only
- secure password hashing
- server-side sessions
- HTTP-only cookie auth
- no OAuth
- no password reset
- no email verification

# Barcode rules

- barcode lookup is lookup only
- local-first behavior where useful
- books and albums are the strongest barcode cases
- movies, TV, and games may remain weaker/manual-fallback cases
- scan page JS should remain small and focused

# Localization rules

- support English and Japanese
- translate presentation/UI only
- keep internal enum values stable and untranslated
- preserve locale through redirects and navigation

# Migration behavior rules

- you may read apps/web and apps/api as reference
- do not make casual/incidental edits to the old app
- do not continue building new features into the old architecture
- build toward the final root-level Go app structure
- when enough replacement coverage exists, old code can be removed intentionally

# Working style

- Use Plan Mode before large edits
- Before coding, summarize the target and list affected files
- Explain how the change moves the repo toward the final Go-only structure
- Prefer complete working code over pseudocode
- Keep packages, templates, handlers, services, and repositories explicit
- After major changes, run relevant checks
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions